Tech Architecture: Implementing Your FeaturesTo map your features cleanly to a React/PHP/MySQL stack, 
you should treat the mobile experience as a Progressive Web App (PWA) or pack it using Capacitor/Cordova 
so your React codebase can run smoothly on iOS and Android devices.

1. The Q-Train Offline Download (Text-Only Mode)

The under-river tunnels connecting Manhattan and Brooklyn are notoriously weak cellular zones. To make text instantly 
available between Canal and DeKalb, your application needs an Offline-First Storage Engine:

React Implementation: Use a browser Service Worker combined with IndexedDB (via a library like Dexie.js).

The Workflow: When the user is above ground, React fires a fetch request to your PHP backend. Your backend 
returns a compressed, text-only JSON payload of the day’s articles. React dumps this text directly into IndexedDB.

The Result: When the train drops underground and loses connection, the React app detects the offline state 
(navigator.onLine === false) and seamlessly pulls the raw text straight from local device storage.

2. Greying-Out and Progress Bars (Gamifying the News)

Giving readers a sense of daily accomplishment is a fantastic user experience choice.

MySQL Schema: Create a user_reads table that acts as a join table linking your users table to an articles table:

CREATE TABLE user_reads (
    user_id INT,
    article_id INT,
    read_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    PRIMARY KEY (user_id, article_id)
);

React State Management: When an article component enters the viewport or gets clicked, fire a quick background POST 
request to your PHP endpoint (/api/read-article.php) to log it in the database. Simultaneously, store the read ID in 
local React state or localStorage so the UI instantly applies a CSS class (opacity: 0.4; filter: grayscale(100%);) 
to grey it out.

Progress Indicator: Calculate the percentage of unread vs. read articles for the day in your SQL query and display 
it at the top of the feed as a clean visual progress bar.

3. Filtering Out "Gag Me" Lifestyles and Custom Categories

The "No-Fluff" Preference System: Assign a hard category_id or tag_id to every incoming article. Provide a settings 
dashboard in React with a list of toggles. If the user unchecks "Lifestyles/Culture", your React app sends those preference 
IDs to your PHP backend, updating a user_preferences table. Your core SQL query will then use a strict WHERE category 
NOT IN (...) clause to ensure that data never even hits their network stream.

Self-Made Custom Folders: Allow users to generate their own collections. Create a custom_folders table (id, user_id, folder_name)
and a folder_articles table (folder_id, article_id). In the UI, a simple dropdown button on each article allows users to instantly 
append the item to their custom folders.


