Part 2: The PHP REST Endpoint (/api/articles.php)

This lightweight, native PHP script handles your exact feature requirements. It reads the logged-in user's 
preferences, filters out the categories they hate (like your "Gag me, Lifestyles" rule), joins the user_reads 
table to tell React which articles to grey out, and returns a clean, text-only JSON payload for the 
Q-train offline mode.

<?php
// 1. Set clean API headers
header("Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *");
header("Content-Type: application/json; charset=UTF-8");
header("Access-Control-Allow-Methods: GET");

// 2. Database Connection using PDO
$host = 'mysql_db'; // Matches the docker-compose service name
$db   = 'modes_for_mods';
$user = 'mfm_user';
$pass = 'mfm_password';
$charset = 'utf8mb4';

$dsn = "mysql:host=$host;dbname=$db;charset=$charset";
try {
     $pdo = new PDO($dsn, $user, $pass, [
         PDO::ATTR_ERRMODE            => PDO::ERRMODE_EXCEPTION,
         PDO::ATTR_DEFAULT_FETCH_MODE => PDO::FETCH_ASSOC,
     ]);
} catch (\PDOException $e) {
     http_response_code(500);
     echo json_encode(["error" => "Database connection failed: " . $e->getMessage()]);
     exit;
}

// 3. Identify the current user (Mocked here, normally parsed from a JWT or session token)
$current_user_id = 1; 

try {
    // 4. Query hidden categories the user hates (e.g., Lifestyles)
    $prefStmt = $pdo->prepare("SELECT category_id FROM user_hidden_categories WHERE user_id = ?");
    $prefStmt->execute([$current_user_id]);
    $hiddenCategories = $prefStmt->fetchAll(PDO::FETCH_COLUMN);

    // Build the conditional string for the SQL statement based on exclusions
    $exclusionClause = "";
    if (!empty($hiddenCategories)) {
        // Creates a string like (?, ?, ?) safely for PDO bind
        $placeholders = implode(',', array_fill(0, count($hiddenCategories), '?'));
        $exclusionClause = "WHERE a.category_id NOT IN ($placeholders)";
    }

    // 5. Query the lightweight text data for the daily feed
    // LEFT JOIN user_reads tells the frontend if an article is already read (is_read = 1 or 0)
    $sql = "
        SELECT 
            a.id, 
            a.title, 
            a.clean_text_content, 
            a.source_url, 
            a.published_at,
            CASE WHEN ur.article_id IS NOT NULL THEN 1 ELSE 0 END AS is_read
        FROM articles a
        LEFT JOIN user_reads ur 
            ON a.id = ur.article_id AND ur.user_id = ?
        $exclusionClause
        ORDER BY a.published_at DESC 
        LIMIT 50
    ";

    $mainStmt = $pdo->prepare($sql);

    // Bind parameters dynamically depending on whether preferences exist
    $params = [$current_user_id];
    if (!empty($hiddenCategories)) {
        $params = array_merge($params, $hiddenCategories);
    }

    $mainStmt->execute($params);
    $articles = $mainStmt->fetchAll();

    // 6. Return the clean payload to React
    http_response_code(200);
    echo json_encode([
        "status" => "success",
        "count" => count($articles),
        "data" => $articles
    ]);

} catch (\Exception $e) {
    http_response_code(500);
    echo json_encode(["error" => "Query failed: " . $e->getMessage()]);
}



Why this benefits Modes for Mods:

Super Lean Payload: Notice it doesn't query heavy HTML blocks, ads, tracker tracking strings, or 
massive tracking cookies. It only sends IDs, titles, and clean text, keeping the fetch operation 
quick enough to download completely right before stepping onto the subway platform.

React UI-Ready: The data payload gives your React app an explicit is_read binary value (0 or 1) for 
every entry. React can immediately read this flag to dim the item or calculate the top progress meter 
bar instantly.

